subQuestions.solutionSteps:
1. Count the number of screenings with attendance rate greater than 70%: There are 5 screenings for Film A, 4 for Film B, 3 for Film C and 3 for Film D, with a total of 5+4+3+3=15 screenings;
2. Count the total number of all screenings: 12+10+9+9=40 screenings;
3. According to the probability formula of classical probability model, probability P = number of qualified screenings / total number of screenings, substitute the data to get P=15/40=3/8.

1. Calculate the probability of selecting a screening with attendance rate greater than 70% for a single film respectively: P(A)=5/12, P(B)=4/10=2/5, P(C)=3/9=1/3;
2. Analyze the situations included in "at least 2 screenings with attendance rate greater than 70%": A and B are greater, C is not; A and C are greater, B is not; B and C are greater, A is not; A, B and C are all greater;
3. According to the multiplication formula of independent event probability and the addition formula of mutually exclusive event probability, calculate the probability of each situation and sum them up:
P = P(A)P(B)(1-P(C)) + P(A)(1-P(B))P(C) + (1-P(A))P(B)P(C) + P(A)P(B)P(C);
4. Substitute the values for calculation: 5/12×2/5×2/3 + 5/12×3/5×1/3 + 7/12×2/5×1/3 + 5/12×2/5×1/3 = 59/180.

